<HL> REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:
Study and Strife</HL>
<DD> 08/18/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
   David Elkind, a child study specialist at Tufts University, writes in the current issue of Parents Magazine that homework does not necessarily have educational value, especially if it becomes a "no man's land" of conflict between teen-agers and their parents. 
The key is whether a teacher is willing to make the commitment to read the student's work thoughtfully and correct it. 
For some teachers, that's probably a no man's land, too. 

</TEXT>
